<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15731</anchor> <rss>jms-00BT.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00BT</addr>  <route>jms-00BT.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title><link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">Event structures</link> and prime algebraic domains</title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p><link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">Event structures</link> are the same thing as prime algebraic domains; on objects, this has been proved many times, but I could only find the correct notion of morphism in a <link href="abbes-2006.xml" type="local" addr="abbes-2006" title="A Cartesian closed category of event structures with quotients">paper of Abbes</link>.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15732</anchor> <rss>jms-00BQ.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00BQ</addr>  <route>jms-00BQ.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Notes on <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structures</link></title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>These notes are inspired and in large part derived from my reading of <link href="staton-winskel-2010.xml" type="local" addr="staton-winskel-2010" title="On the expressivity of symmetry in event structures">Staton and Winskel’s paper on event structures with symmetry</link>.</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15733</anchor> <rss>jms-00BS.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00BS</addr>  <route>jms-00BS.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>A (pre)category of <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structures</link></title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15734</anchor> <rss>jms-00BN.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00BN</addr>  <route>jms-00BN.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Event structure</title>  <meta name="source"><link href="staton-winskel-2010.xml" type="local" addr="staton-winskel-2010" title="On the expressivity of symmetry in event structures">[staton-winskel-2010]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An <em>event structure</em> is defined to be triple <tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( E, \mathsf { Con } _{ E } ,  \leq _E \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> where <tex>E</tex> is a partial order of <em>events</em> partially ordered by the <em>causal dependency relation</em> <tex>\leq _E</tex>, and <tex>\mathsf { Con } _{ E } \subseteq   \mathcal {P} _{ \mathit {fin} } { \mathopen {} \left ( E \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> specifies when a finite subset of <tex>E</tex> is <em>consistent</em>, satisfying the following laws:</p><ol><li>every downset of <tex>E</tex> is finite;</li>
  <li>every singleton set is consistent;</li>
  <li>any subset of a consistent subset is consistent;</li>
  <li>for any consistent subset <tex>x \in \mathsf { Con } _{ E }</tex> and <tex>e \leq  e'</tex> with <tex>e' \in  x</tex>, we have <tex>x \cup { \mathopen {} \left \{ e \right \} \mathclose {}} \in \mathsf { Con } _{ E }</tex>.</li></ol></mainmatter> </tree><p>The definition of <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structure</link> only speaks of <em>finite</em> consistent subsets; these are extended to arbitrary subsets as follows.</p><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15735</anchor> <rss>jms-00BP.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00BP</addr>  <route>jms-00BP.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Consistent subsets of an <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structure</link></title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A subset <tex>x \subseteq  E</tex> of an <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structure</link> is said to be <em>consistent</em> when any finite subset of <tex>x</tex> lies in <tex>\mathsf { Con } _{ E }</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15736</anchor> <rss>jms-00BO.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00BO</addr>  <route>jms-00BO.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Configurations of an <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structure</link></title>  <meta name="source"><link href="staton-winskel-2010.xml" type="local" addr="staton-winskel-2010" title="On the expressivity of symmetry in event structures">[staton-winskel-2010]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <em>configuration</em> of an <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structure</link> <tex>E</tex> is defined to be a <link href="jms-00BP.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BP" title="Consistent subsets of an event structure">consistent</link>, downward-closed subset of <tex>E</tex>. We will write <tex>\mathcal {C} _{ E }</tex> for the set of all configurations of <tex>E</tex> and <tex>\mathcal {C} _{ E }^{ \mathit {fin} }</tex> for the set of <em>finite</em> configurations of <tex>E</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15737</anchor> <rss>jms-00BR.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00BR</addr>  <route>jms-00BR.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Rigid morphisms of <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structures</link></title>  <meta name="source"><link href="staton-winskel-2010.xml" type="local" addr="staton-winskel-2010" title="On the expressivity of symmetry in event structures">[staton-winskel-2010]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <em>rigid morphism</em> of <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structures</link> <tex>{ E } \xrightarrow {{ f }}{ E' }</tex> is a monotone function on events that preserves finite <link href="jms-00BO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BO" title="Configurations of an event structure">configurations</link> and is <em>locally injective</em> in the sense that for any finite <link href="jms-00BO.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BO" title="Configurations of an event structure">configuration</link> <tex>x \in \mathcal {C} _{ E }^{ \mathit {fin} }</tex> and events <tex>e_1,e_2 \in  x</tex> such that <tex>fe_1 = fe_2</tex>, we have <tex>e_1=e_2</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><p>I have not checked whether the appropriate <link href="jms-004K.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004K" title="The structure identity principle">structure identity principle</link> holds for the (pre)category of <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structures</link> and <link href="jms-00BR.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BR" title="Rigid morphisms of event structures">rigid morphisms</link>. If it does not hold, this would suggest that a new <em>univalent</em> definition of event structure is needed.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15738</anchor> <rss>jms-00BU.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00BU</addr>  <route>jms-00BU.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>A subcategory of <link href="jms-00BW.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BW" title="Computation paths">computation paths</link></title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15739</anchor> <rss>jms-00BV.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00BV</addr>  <route>jms-00BV.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Elementary event structures</title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structure</link> is called <em>elementary</em> when every finite set of events is <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">consistent</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15740</anchor> <rss>jms-00BW.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00BW</addr>  <route>jms-00BW.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Computation paths</title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <em>computation path</em> is defined to be a finite <link href="jms-00BV.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BV" title="Elementary event structures">elementary</link> <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structure</link>; we define the category of computation paths to be the full subcategory of <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structures</link> and <link href="jms-00BR.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BR" title="Rigid morphisms of event structures">rigid maps</link> spanned by computation paths.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15741</anchor> <rss>jms-00BX.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Remark</taxon> <addr>jms-00BX</addr>  <route>jms-00BX.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Rigid morphisms between computation paths</title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <link href="jms-00BW.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BW" title="Computation paths">computation path</link> is clearly same thing as a finite poset. A <link href="jms-00BR.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BR" title="Rigid morphisms of event structures">rigid morphism</link> between computation paths corresponds, however, to a <em>monomorphism</em> of posets (not necessarily regular).</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="true" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15742</anchor> <rss>jms-00BT.rss.xml</rss>  <addr>jms-00BT</addr>  <route>jms-00BT.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title><link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">Event structures</link> and prime algebraic domains</title>  </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p><link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">Event structures</link> are the same thing as prime algebraic domains; on objects, this has been proved many times, but I could only find the correct notion of morphism in a <link href="abbes-2006.xml" type="local" addr="abbes-2006" title="A Cartesian closed category of event structures with quotients">paper of Abbes</link>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15743</anchor> <rss>jms-00BN.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-00BN</addr>  <route>jms-00BN.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>10</month> <day>26</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Event structure</title>  <meta name="source"><link href="staton-winskel-2010.xml" type="local" addr="staton-winskel-2010" title="On the expressivity of symmetry in event structures">[staton-winskel-2010]</link></meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>An <em>event structure</em> is defined to be triple <tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( E, \mathsf { Con } _{ E } ,  \leq _E \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> where <tex>E</tex> is a partial order of <em>events</em> partially ordered by the <em>causal dependency relation</em> <tex>\leq _E</tex>, and <tex>\mathsf { Con } _{ E } \subseteq   \mathcal {P} _{ \mathit {fin} } { \mathopen {} \left ( E \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> specifies when a finite subset of <tex>E</tex> is <em>consistent</em>, satisfying the following laws:</p><ol><li>every downset of <tex>E</tex> is finite;</li>
  <li>every singleton set is consistent;</li>
  <li>any subset of a consistent subset is consistent;</li>
  <li>for any consistent subset <tex>x \in \mathsf { Con } _{ E }</tex> and <tex>e \leq  e'</tex> with <tex>e' \in  x</tex>, we have <tex>x \cup { \mathopen {} \left \{ e \right \} \mathclose {}} \in \mathsf { Con } _{ E }</tex>.</li></ol></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks/> <references><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>15744</anchor> <rss>abbes-2006.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Reference</taxon> <addr>abbes-2006</addr>  <route>abbes-2006.xml</route> <date><year>2006</year> <month>1</month> <day>1</day></date> <authors><author><link href="samyabbes.xml" type="local" samyabbes="addr">Samy Abbes</link></author> </authors> <title>A Cartesian closed category of <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structures</link> with quotients</title>  <meta name="doi">10.46298/dmtcs.374</meta><meta name="venue">Discrete Mathematics &amp; Theoretical Computer Science</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We introduce a new class of morphisms for <link href="jms-00BN.xml" type="local" addr="jms-00BN" title="Event structure">event structures</link>. The category obtained is cartesian closed, and a natural notion of quotient event structure is defined within it. We study in particular the topological space of maximal configurations of quotient event structures. We introduce the compression of event structures as an example of quotient: the compression of an event structure <tex>E</tex> is a minimal event structure with the same space of maximal configurations as <tex>E</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></references></backmatter></tree>